<DOC><DOCNO> AP890410-0105 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 1957EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-CalifHeat     04-10 0294</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Calif Heat,0300</SECOND><HEAD>Fog Chases Away Northern California Heat Wave</HEAD><DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Fog and an ocean breeze rolled in over thecoast Monday, ending a sizzling streak of record hot days andensuring traditional chilly weather for the Giants home opener atCandlestick Park.   Inland, however, parts of the San Joaquin Valley were untouchedby the breeze and temperatures were expected to reach near recordlevels again with a high of 97 degrees forecast in Bakersfield.   Unseasonably hot weather over California has been caused by ahigh pressure system between California and Hawaii that held thestorm track to the north, the National Weather Service said.   Southern California got a breath of fresh air during the weekendwhen coastal breezes sent temperatures plunging more than 15degrees in many areas, ending the hottest April week on record.Sunday's high in downtown Los Angeles was 76 degrees, a sharp dropfrom Saturday's 91 and Thursday's 106, a record high for an Aprilday.   San Francisco's forecast for Tuesday predicted morning foggiving way to sunshine and temperatures in the mid 70s to mid 80s.The baseball team's home opener was scheduled Tuesday night.   The San Francisco region's heat wave sent temperatures into the90s for the fourth straight day Sunday and drove sunbathers tobeaches, shoreside boardwalks and reservoirs. Sunday was the fifthstraight day of record temperatess than $50,000 a year.   Many businesses complain that the law, by weighting them downwith paperwork, could have the opposite effect by encouragingabandonment of employee health insurance.</TEXT></DOC>